<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-02-07T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-02-07T19:00:00-05:00" n="839" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d839">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/5113: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-02-07T19:00:00-05:00">February 7, 1929—7
                                p.m.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>54. Your 59, January 28, 3 p.m.</p>
                        <list>
                            <label>1.</label>
                            <item>Have you acted on the Department’s telegram 414 of December 19, 3
                                    p.m.,<note n="75" xml:id="d839fn75"><ref target="frus1928v02#pg_537"><hi rend="italic">Foreign
                                            Relations</hi>, 1928, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>,
                                        p. 537</ref>.</note> and if so with what result?</item>
                            <label>2.</label>
                            <item>Department wishes to avoid any commitment on its part regarding
                                Wang’s note of January 18, and proposal in your paragraph 2 is
                                approved as satisfactory in this regard.</item>
                        </list>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Kellogg</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>